<p><strong>The American Political System: A Q&amp;A Guide</strong></p>
<p><strong>By Ken Kollman</strong></p>
<p><strong>1. What are the three branches of government in the American political system?</strong></p>
<p>The American political system is based on a separation of powers, with three branches of government: the legislative, executive, and judicial branches. The legislative branch, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, makes laws. The executive branch, led by the President, enforces laws and conducts foreign policy. The judicial branch, consisting of the Supreme Court and other federal courts, interprets laws and ensures that they are in accordance with the Constitution.</p>
<p><strong>2. How are members of the House of Representatives and the Senate chosen?</strong></p>
<p>Members of the House of Representatives are elected by the people every two years. Each state is allocated a number of seats in the House based on its population. Senators are elected by the people every six years, with one-third of the Senate up for election every two years.</p>
<p><strong>3. What are the qualifications to be President of the United States?</strong></p>
<p>To be President, a person must be a natural-born citizen of the United States, at least 35 years old, and have lived in the country for at least 14 years.</p>
<p><strong>4. What are the powers of the President?</strong></p>
<p>The President has a wide range of powers, including the ability to veto legislation, appoint members of the Supreme Court and other federal courts, and command the armed forces.</p>
<p><strong>5. What are the responsibilities of the Supreme Court?</strong></p>
<p>The Supreme Court is the highest court in the land and has the power to interpret laws and declare them unconstitutional. The Court also reviews decisions made by lower courts.</p>